{"id":"2103.07909","submitter":"Mark Cannon","authors":"Martin Doff-Sotta, Mark Cannon, Marko Bacic","title":"Predictive energy management for hybrid electric aircraft propulsion\n  systems","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:2004.02582","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We present a Model Predictive Control (MPC) algorithm for energy management\nin aircraft with hybrid electric propulsion systems consisting of gas turbine\nand electric motor components. Series and parallel configurations are\nconsidered. By combining a point-mass aircraft dynamical model with models of\nelectrical losses and losses in the gas turbine, the fuel consumed over a given\nfuture flight path is minimised subject to constraints on the battery, electric\nmotor and gas turbine. The optimization is formulated as a convex problem under\nmild assumptions and its solution is used to define a predictive energy\nmanagement control law that takes into account the variation in aircraft mass\nduring flight. We investigate the performance of algorithms for solving this\nproblem. An Alternating Direction Method of Multipliers (ADMM) algorithm is\nproposed and compared with a general purpose convex interior point solver. We\nalso show that the ADMM implementation reduces the required computation time by\norders of magnitude in comparison with a general purpose nonlinear programming\nsolver, making it suitable for real-time supervisory energy management control.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 14 Mar 2021 12:25:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 12 Nov 2021 12:42:07 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 10 Jun 2022 12:54:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-13"}
